"Pride C., Thunell R., Sigman D., Keigwin L., Altabet M., Tappa E.","Nitrogen isotopic variations in the Gulf of California since the Last Deglaciation: Response to global climate change",1999,"Paleoceanography","14","3",,"397","409",,,10.1029/1999PA900004,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032825094&partnerID=40&md5=82580303c6b9630da3bad3b02f6f8dee","Marine Science Program, Department of Geological Sciences, University of South Carolina, Columbia, SC, United States; Marine Science Institute, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA, United States; Department of Geology and Geophysic, Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, Woods Hole, MA, United States; Department of Geoscience, Princeton University, Guyot Hall, Princeton, NJ, United States; Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry, Center for Marine Science and Technology, University of Massachusetts Dartmouth, North Dartmouth, MA, United States","Pride, C., Marine Science Program, Department of Geological Sciences, University of South Carolina, Columbia, SC, United States, Marine Science Institute, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA, United States; Thunell, R., Marine Science Program, Department of Geological Sciences, University of South Carolina, Columbia, SC, United States; Sigman, D., Department of Geology and Geophysic, Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, Woods Hole, MA, United States, Department of Geoscience, Princeton University, Guyot Hall, Princeton, NJ, United States; Keigwin, L., Department of Geology and Geophysic, Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, Woods Hole, MA, United States; Altabet, M., Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry, Center for Marine Science and Technology, University of Massachusetts Dartmouth, North Dartmouth, MA, United States; Tappa, E., Marine Science Program, Department of Geological Sciences, University of South Carolina, Columbia, SC, United States","High-resolution records of the nitrogen isotopic composition of organic matter (δ15Norg), opal content, and opal accumulation rates from the central Gulf of California reveal large and abrupt variations during deglaciation and gradual Holocene changes coincident with climatic changes recorded in the North Atlantic. Homogenous sediments with relatively low δ15Norg values and low opal content were deposited at the end of the last glacial period, during the Younger-Dryas event, and during the middle to late Holocene. In contrast, laminated sediments deposited in the two deglacial stages are characterized by very high δ15Norg values (&gt;14‰) and opal accumulation rates (29-41 mg cm-2 yr-1). Abrupt shifts in δ15Norg were driven by widespread changes in the extent of suboxic subsurface waters supporting denitrification and were amplified in the central gulf record due to variations in upwelling, vertical mixing, and/or the latitudinal position of the Intertropical Convergence Zone. Copyright 1999 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atlantic Ocean; climate change; denitrification; isotope labeling; marine environment; nitrogen 15; sediment; United States; climate change; Holocene; isotopic composition; last deglaciation; nitrogen isotope; paleoceanography; paleoclimate; Pacific Ocean",,,,,"OCE-8917699, NSF, National Science Foundation; OCE-9201255, NSF, National Science Foundation; OCE-9301413, NSF, National Science Foundation; OCE-9526356, NSF, National Science Foundation; OPP-9530714, NSF, National Science Foundation","Altabet, M.A., Variations in nitrogen isotopic composition between sinking and suspended particles: Implications for nitrogen cycling and particle transformation in the open ocean (1988) Deep Sea Res., Part A, 35, pp. 535-554; Altabet, M.A., Curry, W.B., Testing models of past ocean chemistry using foraminiferal 15N/14N (1989) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 31, pp. 10-619; Altabet, M.A., Francois, R., Sedimentary nitrogen isotopic ratio as a recorder for surface ocean nitrate utilization (1994) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 9, pp. 103-116; Altabet, M.